{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"37f161d2-97ab-4839-9ed4-bfb3589c9c52","content":"NativeAOT doesn't bundle `createdump`, so you must explicitly point the runtime at it. Here's the full configuration:\n\n**Environment variables** for your container:\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  # Enable crash dump generation\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n    value: \"1\"\n  # Dump type: 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n    value: \"4\"\n  # Where to write dumps (%d = PID)\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n    value: \"/tmp/dumps/coredump.%d\"\n  # Required for NativeAOT — runtime doesn't ship createdump\n  - name: DOTNET_CreateDumpPath\n    value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"\n```\n\n**Pod spec changes:**\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: my-app\n      # ... your image, env vars above ...\n      securityContext:\n        capabilities:\n          add:\n            - SYS_PTRACE          # createdump needs ptrace access\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: dump-volume\n          mountPath: /tmp/dumps\n  volumes:\n    - name: dump-volume\n      emptyDir:\n        sizeLimit: 2Gi            # adjust to your app's memory footprint\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`DOTNET_CreateDumpPath`** is the critical one — without it NativeAOT won't find `createdump` and silently skips dump generation.\n- **`SYS_PTRACE`** capability is required because `createdump` uses `ptrace` to snapshot the process.\n- Use an **`emptyDir`** volume (or a PersistentVolumeClaim if you need dumps to survive pod restarts) so dumps aren't lost when the container exits.\n- Set `sizeLimit` proportional to your app's memory — a full dump (`type=4`) can be as large as the process's resident memory.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4dc79751-0db7-4039-99d8-e0a041bec1f3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository doesn't have specific crash dump or NativeAOT content. Let me provide the user with the correct configuration based on my knowledge of .NET NativeAOT crash dump collection.\n\nFor NativeAOT apps in .NET, crash dump collection works differently than CoreCLR. NativeAOT doesn't use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` environment variables the same way CoreCLR does. Instead, for NativeAOT:\n\n1. You need to set environment variables to configure the crash dump behavior\n2. The `createdump` tool path needs to be specified since NativeAOT doesn't bundle it\n\n\n3. I need to configure the specific environment variables that control dump generation, including enabling mini dumps, setting the dump type to full, specifying where dumps should be written, and pointing to the createdump tool location since NativeAOT requires an explicit path to it. For Kubernetes deployments, I need to account for storage and permissions—setting up an emptyDir or persistent volume for the dumps, enabling `shareProcessNamespace` or the right security context for ptrace access, and granting the `SYS_PTRACE` capability so createdump can actually work. These considerations apply across .NET versions, including future releases. Now I'll put together the full configuration.","outputTokens":1112,"requestId":"7641:19B167:E14842:108535E:69FE921D"},"id":"65cc5aaa-9064-4e24-bb18-35f264b7c3b0","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:47:34.557Z","parentId":"d7ab3758-388b-4a2d-8995-125abc5a9605"}
